    notes:
      "## Route Selection — The Practical Decision\n\nBPC-157's multi-route bioavailability is unusual among peptides and creates practical route-selection considerations:\n\n### Subcutaneous (the standard for systemic effects)\n- **Best for:** tendon/ligament repair, joint applications, soft tissue injury, systemic anti-inflammatory effects\n- **Reliable systemic delivery** with predictable plasma levels\n- **Most research peptide community use** — the default unless specific reason for alternative route\n- **Standard injection technique** — insulin syringe, abdominal or thigh sites, rotate\n\n### Oral (well-supported for local gut, debated for systemic)\n- **Best for:** GI protection, IBD adjunct, gut-healing applications, leaky gut contexts, post-NSAID gastric protection\n- **Local gut effects well-supported** by animal model evidence — the gastric juice origin makes oral route mechanistically rational\n- **Systemic effect from oral route is debated** — some absorption documented, but magnitude vs subQ unclear; marketing claims of equivalent systemic effects to injection are not well-supported\n- **For users with primary gut concerns:** oral is the appropriate route\n- **For users wanting systemic effects without injection:** intranasal is more reliable than relying on oral systemic delivery\n\n### Intranasal (emerging research peptide route)\n- **Best for:** systemic effects in users wanting to avoid injection\n- **Reasonable systemic delivery** via olfactory bulb pathway\n- **Less common** than oral or subQ in current research peptide use\n- **Reconstitution: bacteriostatic water or saline; spray into nostril**\n- **Practical alternative** for users uncomfortable with injection but wanting systemic effects\n\n## Beginner Protocol\n**For acute injury (subQ):** 250mcg subQ daily × 1 week (tolerance), then 500mcg subQ daily × 4-8 weeks targeting injury context. Track pain, range of motion, training capacity, healing progress.\n\n**For gut-targeted use (oral):** 500mcg-1mg oral daily × 4-8 weeks for IBD adjunct, post-NSAID gastric protection, or general gut healing. Capsules or sublingual oil per product format.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\n**Comprehensive healing stack (the classical combination):**\n- BPC-157 500mcg subQ daily (or oral for gut priority)\n- TB-500 2-2.5mg subQ weekly (different repair mechanism — actin sequestration vs angiogenesis)\n- KPV 500mcg subQ daily for anti-inflammatory layer\n- Layer with Ipamorelin + CJC-1295 no-DAC pre-sleep for GH-axis recovery support\n- Foundational nutrition: collagen 10-20g/day, vitamin C 1g/day, glycine 3g/day, omega-3 2-4g/day\n- 4-8 week courses for acute injury; chronic low-dose maintenance for ongoing tendon/joint contexts\n\n**Gut-healing protocol:**\n- BPC-157 1mg oral BID\n- KPV 250mcg oral or subQ daily\n- Comprehensive gut foundation (probiotics, glutamine, zinc carnosine, soluble fiber, elimination diet as relevant)\n- Address underlying cause (NSAID use, alcohol, stress, dietary triggers) — peptide support without root-cause work has limited durability\n\n**Cosmetic / skin healing:**\n- BPC-157 250-500mcg subQ daily near affected area or systemic\n- KPV 500mcg subQ daily or topical formulations\n- GHK-Cu (KLOW context) for collagen synthesis support\n- Comprehensive nutrition foundation\n\n## BPC-157 vs Pentadeca-Arginate\n\nPentadeca-Arginate (PDA) is marketed as a 'BPC-157 evolution' with claimed advantages — improved stability, oral bioavailability, modified binding profile. The honest framing (covered in PDA tile):\n\n- **For users running BPC-157 successfully:** continue with BPC-157; PDA's marketing claims are not rigorously verified vs BPC-157\n- **For users with BPC-157 failure or intolerance:** PDA is a reasonable alternative trial\n- **The evidence base for PDA is substantially smaller than BPC-157's** — itself limited but more extensive than PDA's\n\nMost users running healing protocols default to BPC-157 as the established choice; PDA is an emerging compound rather than established alternative.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\n**Subcutaneous:** Lyophilized 5mg vial; reconstitute with 2mL bacteriostatic water → 2.5mg/mL working concentration (0.1mL = 250mcg; 0.2mL = 500mcg). Insulin syringe. Subcutaneous injection, abdominal or thigh sites, rotate. Refrigerate reconstituted; use within 28-30 days.\n\n**Oral:** Per product format — capsules (typically 250mcg-500mcg per capsule), sublingual oil, or reconstituted-and-swallowed liquid. With or without food acceptable.\n\n**Intranasal:** Reconstitute with bacteriostatic water or saline; nasal spray pump or dropper; one nostril per dose typically; alternate nostrils for sustained protocols.\n\n## Synergies\n**TB-500:** the classical healing peptide pairing — different mechanisms (angiogenesis vs actin sequestration); complementary effects on tissue repair. **KPV:** anti-inflammatory complementary mechanism; particularly powerful for gut-healing combined protocols. **Pentadeca-Arginate:** marketed BPC-157 evolution; rarely combined (mechanism overlap). **GH peptides (Ipamorelin + CJC-1295 no-DAC):** GH-axis recovery support; complementary mechanism. **Thymosin Alpha-1:** complementary immune modulation. **GHK-Cu:** copper peptide for collagen synthesis; cosmetic / wound healing pairing. **Foundational nutrition (collagen, vitamin C, glycine, omega-3):** substrate support for tissue repair.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nSikirić laboratory body of work — hundreds of papers from University of Zagreb over 25+ years documenting effects in animal models across virtually every tissue type. Pankov 2014 reviews. Limited Western independent replication. **No completed human RCTs as of catalog last update** — research peptide use has run ahead of formal clinical evaluation despite the substantial Sikirić animal evidence base.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nAnimal model evidence substantial via Sikirić laboratory. Mechanistic case well-established (angiogenesis, growth factor pathways, gastric protection origin). Human RCT evidence essentially absent. The evidence-base reality parallels Khavinson class and Dihexa — single-laboratory or research-community evidence with limited Western RCT replication. Long real-world research peptide community use establishes general tolerability patterns.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: substantial Sikirić laboratory animal evidence base; mechanistically grounded; human RCT evidence essentially absent. Anecdote: extensive use in research peptide / performance recovery / injury rehabilitation communities; subjective effects often perceptible within 1-2 weeks for injury contexts; gut-targeted effects (oral) often noticeable within days for active GI symptoms; tendon/ligament effects accumulate over weeks to months. Decision frame: foundational healing peptide for tissue repair and recovery contexts; multi-route bioavailability provides practical route selection; pairs with TB-500 in classical healing peptide combination; oral route appropriate for gut-priority use; subQ standard for systemic; intranasal emerging alternative; the evidence-base reality (substantial animal evidence, absent human RCTs) warrants honest framing rather than overclaiming or dismissing.",
