    mechanism:
      "Synthetic 11-amino-acid peptide derived from the **helix B domain of erythropoietin (EPO)** — specifically the cytoprotective region of EPO that mediates tissue protection without producing the erythropoietic (red blood cell production) effects that limit therapeutic EPO use. The compound is also known by its development designation **cibinetide**. **Mechanism — Innate Repair Receptor (IRR) activation (the central distinguishing mechanism)**: EPO's tissue-protective effects are mediated by a heteromeric receptor complex called the **Innate Repair Receptor (IRR)** — a heterodimer of the classical EPO receptor (EPOR) and the beta common receptor (βcR / CD131). The IRR is mechanistically distinct from the homodimeric EPOR that mediates erythropoiesis. **Ara-290 selectively activates IRR without activating the homodimeric EPOR** — producing tissue-protective effects without erythropoietic effects. This selectivity is the central design feature: users get EPO's tissue protection benefits without the polycythemia risk that limits EPO's clinical use for tissue protection contexts. **Mechanism — anti-inflammatory effects**: IRR activation produces substantial anti-inflammatory effects via NF-κB pathway modulation, reduced pro-inflammatory cytokine production, and shifted immune cell polarization toward repair phenotypes. **Mechanism — neuroprotection (the central clinical application)**: IRR is highly expressed in nervous tissue; Ara-290 produces substantial neuroprotection in preclinical models including peripheral neuropathy, diabetic neuropathy, sarcoidosis-associated small fiber neuropathy, traumatic nerve injury, and central nervous system insults. The neuropathy applications are the most evidence-supported Ara-290 use cases. **Mechanism — small fiber neuropathy specifically (the FDA orphan drug context)**: Ara-290 has **FDA Orphan Drug designation** for sarcoidosis-associated small fiber neuropathy — a debilitating condition affecting ~10% of sarcoidosis patients with chronic neuropathic pain, autonomic dysfunction, and reduced quality of life. The pharmaceutical development pipeline (Araim Pharmaceuticals) has run clinical trials supporting the orphan drug designation. The FDA orphan drug status is regulatory recognition of the development pipeline rather than full FDA approval — but it represents substantially more clinical development progress than most research peptides. **Mechanism — cardiovascular research applications**: emerging research interest in Ara-290 for cardiovascular tissue protection contexts (post-MI, ischemia-reperfusion injury) leveraging the EPO-derived cytoprotective mechanism without erythropoietic side effects. **Mechanism — diabetic neuropathy (emerging research)**: ongoing research into Ara-290 for diabetic peripheral neuropathy — a substantial unmet medical need affecting millions of diabetic patients; preliminary clinical evidence suggests benefit. **Pharmacokinetics**: subcutaneous administration; relatively short plasma half-life; biological effects sustained substantially longer via downstream IRR signaling and tissue effects. Daily or every-other-day dosing typical.",
