    notes:
      "## Ara-290 — Specialty Neuropathy Use Case\n\nAra-290 occupies a specialty position in the healing peptide landscape — not the default choice for general tissue repair (BPC-157 / TB-500 are more appropriate), but distinctive for specific neuropathy contexts:\n\n**Strongest evidence-supported use case: sarcoidosis-associated small fiber neuropathy**\n- FDA Orphan Drug designation\n- Pharmaceutical development trials (Araim Pharmaceuticals)\n- Substantial unmet medical need\n- The compound was specifically developed for this indication\n\n**Emerging clinical evidence: diabetic peripheral neuropathy**\n- Substantial preclinical evidence\n- Early clinical evidence supportive\n- Massive unmet medical need (millions of diabetic patients)\n- Ongoing pharmaceutical development\n\n**Other neuropathy contexts under research:**\n- Chemotherapy-induced peripheral neuropathy\n- Traumatic nerve injury recovery\n- HIV-associated neuropathy\n- Idiopathic small fiber neuropathy\n\n**Not the appropriate choice for:**\n- General tendon/ligament/soft tissue repair (BPC-157, TB-500 are better)\n- Gut healing (BPC-157, KPV are better)\n- Acute injury recovery (BPC-157, TB-500 + KPV combination is better)\n- General anti-inflammatory use (KPV is better)\n\n## Beginner Protocol\nFor neuropathy contexts: 2mg subQ daily × 1 week (tolerance), then 4mg subQ daily × 8-12 weeks. Track neuropathic pain, sensory symptoms, autonomic function (if relevant for sarcoidosis context). Effects accumulate over weeks to months.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\n**Sarcoidosis-associated small fiber neuropathy (under specialist coordination):**\n- Ara-290 4mg subQ daily × 12-26 weeks (clinical trial protocol pattern)\n- Coordinate with neurologist or sarcoidosis specialist\n- Comprehensive sarcoidosis management foundation (corticosteroids, methotrexate, infliximab as indicated)\n- Symptomatic neuropathic pain management (gabapentin, pregabalin, duloxetine as indicated)\n\n**Diabetic peripheral neuropathy adjunct (under endocrinologist coordination):**\n- Ara-290 4mg subQ daily × 12-26 weeks\n- Comprehensive metabolic management foundation (glycemic control, BP, lipid management)\n- Standard neuropathy management foundation: alpha-lipoic acid 600mg/day, acetyl-L-carnitine 1g BID, methylated B-complex (B12, folate, B6), comprehensive omega-3, vitamin D3\n- Symptomatic neuropathic pain management as needed\n\n**General neuropathy / nerve injury recovery context:**\n- Ara-290 2-4mg subQ daily\n- Comprehensive nerve recovery foundation: B-complex methylated, alpha-lipoic acid, acetyl-L-carnitine, omega-3 high-DHA, vitamin D3, magnesium\n- Lifestyle foundation: glycemic control, weight management, exercise as tolerated, addressing underlying cause (alcohol, medication-induced, autoimmune)\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nLyophilized 16mg vial; reconstitute with 2mL bacteriostatic water → 8mg/mL working concentration (0.5mL = 4mg dose). Insulin syringe or small-volume syringe. Subcutaneous injection, abdominal or thigh sites, rotate. Refrigerate reconstituted; use within 28-30 days.\n\n## Synergies\n**Alpha-lipoic acid:** complementary neuropathy mechanism (antioxidant + nerve metabolism); the foundational neuropathy supplement pairing. **Acetyl-L-carnitine:** complementary nerve metabolism support; ALA + ALCAR combination is the standard neuropathy supplement foundation. **B-complex methylated:** B12/folate/B6 are foundational nerve health nutrients. **Omega-3 high-DHA:** neuroprotection and anti-inflammatory. **BPC-157 / TB-500:** different mechanism healing peptides; rarely combined with Ara-290 (mechanism specialty difference) but can complement in users with both nerve and soft tissue injury contexts.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nDahan 2013 (sarcoidosis small fiber neuropathy phase II trial). Ahmed 2015 (sarcoidosis-associated small fiber neuropathy follow-up). Diabetic neuropathy trials in development. **More clinical trial progress than most research peptides** — the FDA Orphan Drug designation reflects substantial development.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanistic case well-established (IRR activation, EPO-derived cytoprotection without erythropoietic effects). Substantial preclinical evidence base. Emerging clinical evidence in sarcoidosis-associated small fiber neuropathy and diabetic neuropathy. FDA Orphan Drug designation represents regulatory recognition of development progress. Long-term safety profile under investigation via ongoing clinical development.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: substantial preclinical evidence; emerging clinical evidence in specific neuropathy contexts; FDA Orphan Drug designation; pharmaceutical development pipeline ongoing. Anecdote: less common in research peptide community use vs BPC-157/TB-500 (specialty compound for specific use cases); subjective effects on neuropathic pain often perceptible over 4-8+ weeks; not a default healing peptide choice. Decision frame: specialty repair peptide for specific neuropathy contexts; appropriate for sarcoidosis-associated small fiber neuropathy, diabetic peripheral neuropathy, and broader nerve injury / inflammation contexts; FDA Orphan Drug status distinguishes from typical research peptides; pairs with comprehensive neuropathy management foundation; not a general tissue repair choice (BPC-157 / TB-500 are more appropriate for general healing).",
