    notes:
      "## Thymosin Alpha-1 vs Thymosin Beta 4 / TB-500 — The Distinction\n\nThis distinction is the most important framing for users encountering both compounds:\n\n**Thymosin Alpha-1 (this entry):**\n- 28-amino-acid sequence\n- TLR9 activation; T-cell maturation; immune system enhancement\n- Pharmaceutical heritage (Zadaxin, 35+ countries)\n- Use cases: chronic viral infection, immune deficiency, immunosenescence, cancer immunotherapy adjunct\n- Twice-weekly dosing typical\n\n**Thymosin Beta 4 / TB-500 (separate entry in this batch):**\n- 43-amino-acid TB4 native or LKKTETQ short fragment (TB-500)\n- Actin sequestration; tissue repair; angiogenesis; anti-inflammatory\n- Research peptide; no pharmaceutical approval\n- Use cases: tendon/ligament/soft tissue repair, wound healing, cardiac repair research\n- Weekly dosing typical\n\nUsers asking about 'Thymosin' should specify which one — they are not interchangeable, despite the shared family name. The historical naming reflects both compounds' thymic peptide research origins, but mechanistically and clinically they are distinct.\n\n## Beginner Protocol\n750mcg-1.6mg subQ × first dose to assess tolerance, then 1.6mg subQ twice weekly × 4-12 weeks. Track immune-related markers if relevant (frequency of viral illnesses, recovery from infections, energy / wellbeing). Pharmaceutical Zadaxin protocols use longer durations (6-12+ months for chronic viral infection contexts).\n\n## Advanced Protocol\n**Chronic viral infection adjunct (under specialist coordination):**\n- Thymosin Alpha-1 1.6mg subQ twice weekly\n- Comprehensive viral / immune management foundation under hepatologist or infectious disease specialist coordination\n- Long-duration protocols (6-12+ months) per Zadaxin clinical experience\n\n**Age-related immunosenescence support:**\n- Thymosin Alpha-1 1.6mg subQ twice weekly cycled 12-16 weeks on / 4-8 weeks off\n- Comprehensive immune foundation: vitamin D3 5000 IU/day + K2 MK-7, zinc 30mg/day, selenium 200mcg/day, NAC 600mg BID (glutathione precursor), comprehensive nutrition\n- Lifestyle foundation: sleep optimization, stress management, exercise, adequate protein\n\n**Cancer immunotherapy adjunct (under oncologist coordination):**\n- Thymosin Alpha-1 as adjunct in research / off-label investigational contexts\n- Coordinate with oncologist; not validated standard care but mechanistically rational research interest\n\n**Comprehensive recovery / immune optimization stack:**\n- Thymosin Alpha-1 1.6mg subQ twice weekly\n- BPC-157 / TB-500 for tissue repair if relevant (different use case but compatible)\n- Comprehensive immune supplement foundation\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\n**Zadaxin (pharmaceutical):** Per product label; specific reconstitution from pharmaceutical packaging.\n\n**Compounded / research peptide:** Lyophilized 5mg vial; reconstitute with 2mL bacteriostatic water → 2.5mg/mL working concentration (0.64mL = 1.6mg dose). Insulin syringe. Subcutaneous injection, abdominal or thigh sites, rotate. Refrigerate reconstituted; use within 28-30 days.\n\n## Synergies\n**Vitamin D3 + K2 MK-7:** foundational immune support; vitamin D status affects immune function broadly. **Zinc:** foundational immune mineral; T-cell function. **Selenium:** glutathione peroxidase cofactor; immune cell function. **NAC:** glutathione precursor; immune cell antioxidant defense. **BPC-157 / TB-500:** different use case (tissue repair vs immune modulation) but compatible — users with both injury and immune contexts can run both. **Cancer immunotherapy agents (under oncologist):** immune system enhancement potentially synergistic.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nSubstantial Zadaxin clinical trial database supporting hepatitis B/C indications in 35+ countries. Camerini 2015 hepatocellular carcinoma adjuvant. King 2010 review of clinical applications. Multiple smaller trials in immune deficiency, cancer immunotherapy adjunct, and immunosenescence contexts. **Substantially more clinical trial evidence than typical research peptides.**\n\n## Evidence Quality\nPharmaceutical heritage (Zadaxin in 35+ countries) establishes substantial safety and efficacy data. Mechanism well-characterized (TLR9 activation, T-cell maturation). Long-term safety profile established via decades of pharmaceutical use. Specific application evidence: hepatitis B/C strongest; broader immune applications mechanistically grounded with smaller specific trial bases.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: substantial pharmaceutical clinical evidence base (Zadaxin) — substantially more than typical research peptides; mechanism well-characterized; long-term safety established. Anecdote: extensive use in research peptide community for immune support, chronic viral infections, age-related immune decline; subjective effects on immune function (frequency of illness, recovery from infections) often noticeable over 8-12+ weeks. Decision frame: foundational immune-modulating peptide with substantial pharmaceutical heritage; appropriate for chronic viral infection contexts (under specialist coordination), age-related immunosenescence, immune deficiency contexts; explicit distinction from Thymosin Beta 4 / TB-500 essential to avoid confusion; pairs with comprehensive immune foundation.",
